But sometimes I'm just compelled to create and let others into my process. I've gotten great feedback and I hope that this is another one of those pieces. Having a little hang out to inspire people to pursue their passions. And to do that, no matter what. We all need to learn to lose our excuses, and instead seek out all the reasons to live out iour dreams.

The Turkish March by Mozart was played all throughout the Truman show and yet 90% of people go to seaside beach in Florida. Don't realize it. That movie is one that can be watched over and over. It's a subtle take on human society. How each one of us, except the reality we've been presented with. This doesn't just mean main stream, media, entertainment, industry, social media, and all the other means of communication, but the reality of looking in the mirror and thinking things can't change.  Truman comes to this reality that there is more world out there for him. There's a part of us that doesn't want him to find out when we are watching the movie. It's like in the matrix when you have to take the red pill to see the reality you live in. The blue pill or the road frequently traveled is the easy road. But absolutely nothing good and definitely nothing. Great comes from taking the easy road. In fact, the easy road isn't easy. It makes life harder. If that isn't the height of irony, I don't know what is.  If you feel like you have a noble destiny, and you were sent here to impact the lives of others, and not merely just be a famous actor or singer, but somebody who truly changes peoples lives through your actions, to let anything hold you back and don't settle for mediocrity.

So… If you listen really carefully, you can hear the raging storm behind the piano. The door was cracked open so there's a couple times lightning and thunder was close by. This really inspired me to just play and not think. My favorite in profs seem to come all by themselves. it's often weeks before I learn how to play what I just came up with.

Scoring the storm.... this is an extension of my music theory studies giving me space to musically narrate the storm.  Y'all know my instrumentals are typically piano based.  But strings, horns, orchestral sounds have been my jam for 30 years.  Coming back to these sounds with hyper creativity and having the guts to jump outside the key has been satisfyingly momentous.  There really is not bottom to creativity.  If you only learn one new musical trick—commonly know as music theory—every day, you have a injection of knowledge, wisdom and freedom to experiment:  life is good.  Music is great. God is amazing!  All creation echoes His creative power! 🙏🙌🏽. P.S.  if you were tagged, that means I think you're truly creative!!! If you weren't, I probably just missed you because I have a ton on my plate right now.

This an impromptu that I title "A mid summer sketch" came to me while working on a separate piece from Shostakovich's Concerto No. two. This often happens. I'm working on something else, and I look at the piano and on way and notes seem to jump out at my hands and in my ears. Though I don't deserve to be mentioned in the same sentence as Bach, Mozart, Beethoven, Chopin, Rachmaninoff, and the other greats, I do have one thing in common with them. I'm only writing down when I hear in my head. But in my case, I don't write it. I play it.  I suppose I should start working on my notation skills a little bit more.

There's a reason I'm titled this thusly.  If you listen, carefully, you'll hear very loud crickets in the background. Crickets typically chirp on an "A"  note. So I played this entire improv in the key of a miner while modulating into some other keys and still keeping A as the center piece  and keeping rhythm with the crickets out my window.  What people don't realize is that the sound of crickets actually stimulates a part of our brain that induces sleep. So this… This particular improv… I believe… Will! Make! You! Sleep!

Me to a T! I often wonder what happened, right after I create one of my improvisations. It doesn't feel like me. Yet it is more me than anything I've done. A reflection of what's been going through my mind. A reflection of my dreams. A reflection of my hopes. And I pray… A reflection of what God is doing in me, and through me.  The Chopin nocturne I've chosen for the background is one that haunts me every time I play it.  It dares me to make such extraordinary leaps into musical mystery and fulfill my melodic destiny.  When this happens, I have to respond!  This is why I NEVER audit my improvs.  Though they sometimes end up as music beds for a song or songs or even projects, the raw form has to be given its chance to breath.

They played a joke on me when she tried to sing for me and said it's simply atrocious. I stopped immediately and started trying to fix her voice. They just laughed, and then she saying for real. friend of mine was agreeing with me that Christmas is for hopeful Romantics. This was my improvisation reflecting that view.  I literally never know how these are going to turn out when I'm playing them. I just let go and let my fingers do whatever they want. To me it's about perfect imperfections. But for a long time I just wanted to be creative and I didn't want to get better. And I realized my creativity had limits. So I went and learned a bunch of Bach, a whole bunch of Chopin, little bit of Mozart, LiLiszt and Schubert. And immerse myself in very diverse music styles all my life. Now it's time to put all my creativity to the test. Which literally means, I don't need to rest. I just need to express.

Things will never be the same.  I co-wrote this with a dear friend about 20 years ago.  It's kind of unbelievable to think how much life a person can live in in 20 years. Feels like 4 separate lifetimes in 2 decades.  Even now, I look at all my voice memos and hope to be able to sort through the 2,500 songs I've written, and record or pitch as many as possible. Today is finally the day! After more than two years in the making, I am so proud to finally be able to share this song, ‘Meant To Be’ with you!

And the making of this song was truly meant to be in so many ways.  Here is Part 1 of the story of how ‘Meant To Be’ came to be:

1. I wrote the first draft of this song in 15 minutes one evening this time of year in 2021. That night I questioned if I was truly meant to pursue music.

2. A few weeks later, @micsviews and I were visiting @jadethesongwriter and @jonblaze27, and I told her I was in desperate need of production for the songs I had written. Jade just so happened to have a spare beat for me, produced by @ccvscc. I tried it on ‘Meant To Be’, and in the very first take, the entire melody line was written!

3. 18 months later, and I was finally in the middle of production on this album. Then out of nowhere @brettmanning_ss connected with me on IG, resulting in me coming to Nashville for the very first time for his and @singingsuccess vocal retreat. I had been a VIP member for years at this point and had been working with Brett’s CD’s since I was 15, so this was a dream come true! This trip was truly a game changer. I prayed to find my sound, and I left achieving just that.

There, I met @malcolmspringerproducer  @ryanthemusicman  @rickbarkermusic  @themattellenberger  @tjacksons  @myersmusicmedia @larrypareigis @claymills2  @janelnabong_ @julia.music._  @zandiholup  @madisonsariah  and countless others. Had it not been for everyone mentioned above, I would not have found my true sound.  And all this I owe to @brettmanning_ss. You have truly been a miracle and Godsend in my life, and the incredible impact you’ve had in my life 🙌🏼

I can’t finish sharing part 1 of this story without mentioning @ccvscc, @nickmorandrums, @cpurductions, @malcolmspringerproducer, @tlgent1 & @mayfly97 who were instrumental in the creation and execution of Meant To Be, and @brittanybrunck @mandy_m_moore @adonisadvincula @dayanamendoza.us @filmeditrepeat @usedtobevalentines @brianbrunckhorst and once again @_mic.g for your support and input throughout this process. I love you all and am so grateful for this journey!

What child is this… Is a timeless melody that is shared by a dozen other songs. Sometimes I start playing a song I played on my life and I just hear differently. This is one of those times.

Who is totally working on something different and suddenly had the inkling to just try to harmonize only four notes in my right hand. So this melody has only four sequential notes in it. Literally a half an octave.  I find that we don't see the brilliance in the simple things. With music, you can harmonize two or three notes with multiple chord, progressions and create such vast color. In fact, music allows you to create an entire world inside of a persons head. Things that you'll see from this one shot improv should demonstrate, but I've tried to do here.  Enjoy

Throwback to 2017 Christmas with my kids. 10 and 11 at the time.  Time never stops or rewinds.  But memories can help stretch time and make sense of the present:

This improv moves straight  through me often when I'm practicing Chopin, Bach, Mozart, Schubert and Liszt.  My best description of this one is just pure emotive. The patient understanding of where music takes you. Not wanting to run a head of the Melody. But be in the middle of it. The little counterpoint at the end of the motif hit me as a tribute to all the hours of playing Bach.  I was really satisfied where this one took me.  I trust you'll see it too!

Vocal and EP old school "Manhattans/ Stylistics/ Bee Gees/ Jackson 5/ Earth, Wind and Fire/ influenced, pouring though my veins.  This improv could use some lyrics.  If this slams you with some inspiration and you wanna hit me up, DM and we'll see if your idea fits my intention.
The left hand makes the right hand"a Melody more interesting .  Sometimes, playing in the dark forces you to let go of your senses and see what will happen. No plan. Just letting go

Sometimes it feels strange to just let your fingers move, and then we call that an improv. For me, I feel like my fingers have a mind of their own. They just know what my brain can't comprehend. In this case, I've been hearing so many great romance stories, and listening to some of the deepest music ever written. No doubt those influences are scattered throughout these melodies. In the end, every chord and combination has been used in some way or another.  There's something about dusk that makes you feel hopeful and helpless at the same time. Completely vulnerable. This is when I do my best stuff.  Enjoy!
Every now and then.....

This definitely has a classical composer influence. The word jumped the tracks in the middle, the chords to resemble something familiar in the beginning. The Melody is completely my own.  But, I figured out some thing. Improvisation is about trust. Belief. Faith.  And the more you let go, the more God continues to pour into you.  It becomes a sort of healthy addiction.
